\begin_layout Subsection
Example: finite dimensions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider 
\begin_inset Formula $H=\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset

 and a symmetric operator 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in L\left(\mathbb{C}^{n}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Choose an orthonormal eigenvector basis such that 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has the matrix representation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A & =\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\lambda_{1} &  & 0\\
 & \ddots\\
0 &  & \lambda_{n}
\end{array}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 are real, but there can be degeneracies, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i\not=j$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
A^{2} & =\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\lambda_{1}^{2} &  & 0\\
 & \ddots\\
0 &  & \lambda_{n}^{2}
\end{array}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Similarly we can compute polynomials of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The Stone-Weierstraß approximation yields for 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in C^{0}\left(\sigma\left(A\right),\mathbb{C}\right)$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f\left(A\right) & =\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
f\left(\lambda_{1}\right) &  & 0\\
 & \ddots\\
0 &  & f\left(\lambda_{n}\right)
\end{array}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since the spectrum
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sigma\left(A\right) & =\left\{ \lambda_{1},\ldots,\lambda_{n}\right\} 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

is a finite set, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $C^{0}\left(\sigma\left(A\right)\right)=\mathcal{B}\left(\sigma\left(A\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The spectral measure for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega\subseteq\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E_{\Omega} & :=\chi_{\Omega}\left(A\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
\chi_{\Omega}\left(\lambda_{1}\right) &  & 0\\
 & \ddots\\
0 &  & \chi_{\Omega}\left(\lambda_{n}\right)
\end{array}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 is the projection operator on the eigenspaces, for which the eigenvalues
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 lie in 
\begin_inset Formula $\Omega$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\int f\left(\lambda\right)\dd E_{\lambda} & =\sum_{j=1}^{n}f\left(\lambda_{j}\right)E_{\left\{ \lambda_{j}\right\} }
\end{align*}

\end_inset

More specifically, let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{j}$
\end_inset

 be an orthonormal eigenvector basis, 
\begin_inset Formula $Au_{j}=\lambda_{j}u_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u_{i},u_{j}\right\rangle =\delta_{ij}$
\end_inset

.
 Then for any 
\begin_inset Formula $v\in\mathbb{C}^{n}$
\end_inset

 let 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}^{\left(\lambda\right)},\ldots,u_{\mu}^{\left(\lambda\right)}$
\end_inset

 be all eigenvectors with the eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $Au_{k}^{\left(\lambda\right)}=\lambda u_{k}^{\left(\lambda\right)}$
\end_inset

, so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E_{\left\{ \lambda\right\} }v & =\sum_{k=1}^{\mu}u_{k}^{\left(\lambda\right)}\left\langle u_{k}^{\left(\lambda\right)},v\right\rangle 
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 is the projection on the eigenspace 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle u^{\left(k\right)}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

